{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":61907,"duration_api_ms":61859,"num_turns":15,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"62422f51-08e2-4b6b-95df-d40480fd67c0","total_cost_usd":0.4428005,"usage":{"input_tokens":11,"cache_creation_input_tokens":33262,"cache_read_input_tokens":349366,"output_tokens":2407,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":33262,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":11,"outputTokens":2407,"cacheReadInputTokens":349366,"cacheCreationInputTokens":33262,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.4428005,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Both amendments identify genuine gaps. Amendment fr-5-f1c7b7b6 correctly identifies that legacy rows with plan_hash=None are never repaired even when the snapshot hash hasn't changed since the row was created — the blanket prohibition conflates two distinct scenarios. Amendment fr-5-39bc594e correctly identifies that the round-trip tests are example-based and cannot detect new optional fields added with skip_serializing_if, plus the duplicated schema remains a maintenance hazard.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-5-f1c7b7b6","decision":"accept","rationale":"The code at lines 2927-2931 and 3257-3261 applies a blanket prohibition against snapshot-based plan_hash backfill for all existing rows, but the stated rationale (avoid mislabeling a v1 attempt as v2 when persist_plan() advances the snapshot hash) only applies to one of two distinct cases. Case 1: the snapshot hash has advanced past the attempt's original plan version — backfilling would mislabel, so skipping is correct. Case 2: a legacy row was created before auto-population existed (plan_hash=None) and the snapshot hash has NOT changed since — this is a safe repair opportunity that is currently missed. The new auto-population at line 2958-2960 only runs for brand-new inserts, and backfill_running_entry at line 2733-2748 only fills plan_hash when the caller explicitly provides it. If callers keep omitting plan_hash on retry/completion calls, legacy rows complete with plan_hash=None permanently. The fix is straightforward: when an existing row has plan_hash=None, compare the snapshot hash against the row's started_at or other provenance to determine if backfill is safe, rather than blanket-skipping. This is a real defect in the repair/migration path for Issue 3."},{"amendment_id":"fr-5-39bc594e","decision":"accept","rationale":"The round-trip tests at lines 3768-3812 populate all fields with Some values and verify the round-trip succeeds, but they cannot structurally detect drift. The critical failure mode: if a new field is added to StartJournalDetailsPayload or CompletionJournalDetailsPayload in model.rs with `skip_serializing_if = Option::is_none` and defaults to None, the render function will never emit it when it's None, so the fs adapter's deny_unknown_fields won't trigger and the round-trip test passes perfectly — despite the fs struct lacking the field entirely. The test only catches drift when a new REQUIRED field is added or when a test case happens to set the new optional field to Some. Meanwhile the duplicated structs (fs.rs lines 2279-2339 vs model.rs lines 353-386) remain a concrete maintenance hazard. A structural guard — such as a compile-time assertion that both types implement the same trait, or a test that serializes a payload with ALL optional fields set to Some — would close this gap. The current example-based approach gives a false sense of safety."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"82eb9f13-d9a1-40ed-a668-0a8b3b20cc94"}
